Additional pitfall

## [1] "overestimation of litter mass loss by cleaning the litter. Dear and boar pulling up and chewing on the litterbags. One solution is a fence. High unexplained site-to-site variation in decomposition rates.. Cages always change microclimate. I tested several alternatives to litterbags such as tethering and marking with plastic paint but they had problems worse than litterbags. Leaf litter decomposition is usually disconected in studies and theory with recent advances in soil carbon research (eg mineral interactions). producing enough labelled litter (e.g. Leppert, K.N., Niklaus, P.A., Scherer-Lorenzen, M., 2017. Does species richness of subtropical tree leaf litter affect decomposition, nutrient release, transfer and subsequent uptake by plants? Soil Biology and Biochemistry 115, 44-53.). A main problem is that any treatment manipulating insect access also affects microclimatic conditions. This is both hard to avoid and to quantify. \nMoreover, insects affect decomposition not only directly but also indirectly via interactions with microbes. Separating these direct and indirect effects is challenging.. Convincing collaborators to follow protocols in a distributed project. Materials not standing up to extreme climates. Substrates decaying faster than expected meaning changes in harvest dates. Probably many more!. We have so few data of litter bags or bait lamina test for tropical regions. Every new project request a pre-test to determine the exposure time. Furthermore, considering contaminated sites, what is the best plant material for use in litter bags? Plants from the contaminated site could contain contaminants (and be avoided by fauna), while plants from outside the area could be like an island for the organisms (preffered instead of that from the site). Moreover, in ecological risk assessment of contaminated site which include different land uses (e.g.: residential areas with gardens, forest area, plantations), how to discrimate the effects of contaminants and land use?. surface litter bags being displaced and not in full contact with the soil surface.  As above - changing to a different substrate allowed me to change the context of the question (natural substrate was 'litter' and on surface; artificial substrate was artificial, so I inserted into soil). elephants and pigs dig up my plots. Tradeoffs in deciding the initial litter mass between minimizing a substrate-induced response and detecting a realistic in situ substrate response.. The mesh size clearly interacts with the external environment, to create artifacts (e.g. Bradford et al. 2002 Oikos)"

Possible solutions

## [1] "Solutions depend on the scientific question. e.g., for mineral contamination, do you wanna assess microbial community composition? If no, you can wash the leaves gently in a siever, if yes, you must use a brush to avoid removing microbial communities.. Snow problem; (i) adapting samling dates, (ii) long stick with colour labels on top. Comparing litter bag decomposition with mass balance approaches to estimating decay constants. We correct for soil contamination by subtracting ash content, which was measured by burning the litter samples in a muffle furnace.. Control dowel in wood decomposition. litterbags containing only mesh that would trap roots or moss growing through bags. Soil contamination inside litterbags is quite common but easy to deal with a bit of water cleaning. Contamination by exogenous plant material always happen (unless really small mesh sizes), but in my case this material was easy to remove in the lab because plant species were different from my litter mixtures. The temporal reproducibility is always an issue, but we performed a combination of 3 temporal harvest + statistical approach to how the influence of biotic and abiotic filters of decomposition change over multiple mass loss intervals (García-Palacios et al Ecol Lett 2016). Soil contamination: Not sure what the problem is, but in litter bag experiments I generally only encounter clay intrusion. Weight loss correction then is relatively easily done by measuring shifts in mineral content of the bag (LOI, C/N, sequential extraction etc).\n\nContamination with exogenous material: As I incubate tea-bags below the soil surface, I have often encountered root ingrowth to mineralising (green) tea bags in soils with N-nutrient limitation. Given the relatively short incubation time of 3 months, roots are generally easy to remove as they are still intact and stick to the mesh.\n\nDetermining the harvest date: I think that decomposition experiments based on the assumption of a constant k make the outcome of decomposition experiments strongly dependent on the chosen incubation time. I therefore mostly calculate a two or three phase decomposition model by measuring 1) a time series or 2) materials with different levels of decomposability under the assumption that these can be quantified by determination of the acid unhydrolysable residue. See oa \n\nTea Bag Index: a novel approach to collect uniform decomposition data across ecosystems\nJA Keuskamp, BJJ Dingemans, T Lehtinen, JM Sarneel, MM Hefting\nMethods in Ecology and Evolution 4 (11), 1070-1075,\n\nDisturbance: this is of course highly context-dependent. I have had experience with sheep, mice, termites, crabs, fish, and farmers :). Two papers specifically addressing decomposition experiments and disturbance:\n\nAn affordable and reliable assessment of aquatic decomposition: Tailoring the Tea Bag Index to surface waters\nLMS Seelen, G Flaim, J Keuskamp, S Teurlincx, RA Font, D Tolunay, ...\nWater research 151, 31-43\n\nValidation and extension of the Tea Bag Index to collect decomposition data from termite-rich ecosystems\nA Teo, NP Kristensen, JA Keuskamp, TA Evans, M Foo, RA Chisholm\nPedobiologia 80, 150639. contamination by in-growing roots: needs tedious sorting of the litter bags. Harvest date: use dummy-bags to determine a certain threshold of litter mass loss (which depends on the research question). For soil contamination, I rather focus on C and N loss rather than mass loss to remove the mineral contamination. For animals disturbance, chicken wire placed on top of litterbags/field microcosms works very well.. Soil contamination during decomposition: using [C] or ashing\nContamination by exogenous material (e.g. plant parts): careful sorting\nDetermining the harvest date: sacrifical set of litter / previous literature results / sequential harvests\nDisturbance (humans, animals, weather conditions,...): physical protection (grid) / use of a litter layer on top of bags. 1. Brushes/combustion, 2. Separation, 3. Scale up to regional and global, 4. Increase to many years, 5. Bayesian hierarchical analyses, 6. Change materials used although didn't work in all cases, 7. Discussed with collaborators, 8. Increased replication but some conditions are hard to overcome, e.g., fire in savannas.. Exogenous material: in my studies, it was easy to identify and remove. Determine the harvest date: we performed a pre test before the main experiment, but it takes time.. I switched from a natural (recalcitrant) plant source that was at the field sites to an artificial one (cellulose) to match temporal data collection and to better examine intra-annual climate effects. Determined harvest date with a trial experiment with a wide range of harvests.. We pick out roots that colonize litter and use that as an additional measure. For mineral soil contamination, we measure percentage C or ash the litter material"

Interesting points to discuss:

Phylosphere and homefieldadvantage

Microclimate

I am not sure that a focus on decomposition and decomposition experiments is useful, as separating decomposition of litter (traditionally done by forest ecologists) and soil organic matter dynamics (traditionally done by agroecologists and more recently soil biogeochemists) has caused the issues that prompted your workshop. I suggest to also question the premise of your question...

Your focus is on plant residues, but decomposition of animals or fungi is also very important for C- and nutrient fluxes, and face similar challenges in methodology. So, perhaps either add a statement why you focus on plants only, or broaden the perspective to include such organisms and their decomposition too.
